<TEXT>
firefighters declared a temporary victory friday in their battle 
to keep a forest fire out of a small montana town and forest 
officials warned that more lightning and dry hot weather were 
forecast this weekend 
its like sitting on a time bomb said scott phillips 
recreation officer for the sawtooth national recreation area in 
central idaho if we can get through this weekend without a 
conflagration it will be a miracle 
forests and rangeland burned friday in parts of wyoming 
especially in yellowstone national park and in idaho montana 
oregon washington utah and california 
the boise interagency fire center the logistics command for the 
national battle against forest fires reported more than 25000 
firefighters military and support personnel on the lines of more 
than three dozen major fires in the west 
fire center spokesman arnold hartigan called it the most 
severe fire season in almost 30 years more than 35 million 
acres have burned twothirds of that in alaska and suppression 
costs already exceed 250 million 
the fire season is anything but over the 30day weather 
forecast calls for continued unseasonably hot and dry weather for 
the pacific northwest and northern rockies hartigan said record 
highs were forecast during the weekend in oregon and washington 
with a threat of lightning 
forest service officials asked people to stay out of forests in 
central montana and restrictions on such things as open campfires 
were tightened in idaho and washington many forests in oregon were 
closed to recreational use 
logging activity was shut down statewide in washington on 
public and private land because of fire concern the weyerhaeuser 
co closed all its timberlands to public access until further 
notice 
the focus of attention friday in and around yellowstone where 
some 550000 acres have been charred was the small town of west 
yellowstone mont just outside the parks west entrance it was 
threatened by flames just over a mile away that were spreading from 
the 118000acre north fork fire inside the park that had grown by 
nearly 10000 acres since thursday morning 
bulldozers helicopters and back fires stalled the advance of 
the fire friday but gusty winds swept a swath of flame south of 
the town and a wind change predicted for monday raised concerns the 
blaze could move back toward the community 
in my judgment this community is very defensible denny 
bungartz the north fork fires incident commander told about 60 
townspeople 
he said firetrucks had pumped 5000 gallons of water into dry 
brush around a warehouse at the park boundary and 50 fire engines 
would be in town during the night to hose down buildings if 
necessary 
to the east and north of town the madison river formed a 
natural fire break firefighters improved on that barrier by 
bulldozing fire lines and lighting backfires exhausting the 
forests fuel before the main fire could reach the river as 
helicopters dropped water on the area 
residents of the small town with a yearround population of 
750 prepared to evacuate but most stayed put friday most of the 
people leaving town were tourists who decided to spend their labor 
day weekend somewhere less smoky 
curious onlookers filled the streets friday as afternoon winds 
blew away the smoky haze 
im packed up and ready to go said david powell owner of a 
hamburger stand downtown i left la because i couldnt stand the 
smog i dont like this stuff 
some people were driving in the other direction because west 
yellowstone will play host to hundreds of square dancers this 
weekend for the knothead jamboree resident dance caller orvile 
pittam says its been sponsored by square dance groups in utah 
idaho wyoming and montana every labor day weekend for 37 years and 
attracts up to 800 people 
ken takata west yellowstone chamber of commerce president said 
that while there have been some cancellations because of the fires 
its too early to tell what the overall effect will be 
we want people to know that right now conditions are pretty 
good he said friday weve had some bad press that west 
yellowstone is being evacuated and thats just not the case we 
hope it will be business as usual 
elsewhere in yellowstone the clover mist fire had covered 
232400 acres after growing 1000 acres in 24 hours the snake 
river complex of fires was stable at about 156500 acres and the 
wolf lake fire grew slightly to 40500 acres said fire information 
officer brian morris 
north of yellowstone in southcentral montana firefighters in 
the absarokabeartooth wilderness changed their tactics friday on a 
49800acre wilderness fire that jumped fire lines four days in a 
row 
fire information officer chris comstock said friday that 
officals changed their strategy from building fire lines to setting 
backfires because our method of approach right now hasnt been 
effective in catching this fire 
fire bosses in idaho used a second day of light wind to gain 
more ground against the worst of idahos 17 wildfires with more 
than 3000 firefighter and support personnel still battling fires 
that had burned more than 75000 acres 
only the 40300acre tepee butte fire remained out of control in 
oregon in the wallowawhitman national forest and the hells 
canyon national recreation area it was 25 percent contained 
friday officials said 
by friday fires that raged through tinderdry california 
forests were dying down with all reported contained or under 
control 
a new forest fire near salt lake city forced the evacuation of a 
few homes on friday the states largest fire was a 2000acre 
blaze fanned by ridgetop winds near northern utahs pineview 
reservoir 
the fire was initially declared under control late tuesday at 
525 acres but roared to life again late wednesday when gusts fanned 
hot spots and pushed flames over fire lines 
</TEXT>
