<TEXT>
the expatriate daughter of a near 
legendary hero assassinated 40 years ago is helping to unify vast 
but potentially chaotic antigovernment forces in burma 
aung san leader of burmas independence struggle was gunned 
down at the age of 32 before as many have suggested the world 
of workaday politicking he was about to enter could mar his image 
some media reports have compared his daughter aung san suu kyi 
with philippine president corazon aquino and benazir bhutto of 
pakistan women from nationally prominent families who led or lead 
opposition forces 
the 43yearold daughter last week drew crowds of up to 400000 
to hear her call for democracy after 26 years of authoritarian 
rule some diplomats and burmese analysts believe she will be only 
a transitional figure but one who could help unify disparate 
groups and prevent a plunge into anarchy 
aung sans daughter was thrust unwittingly into the political 
arena after coming to rangoon from her home in england in april to 
care for her ailing mother 
she saw all the commotion and turmoil the rioting and 
demonstrators getting killed said burmese emigre spokesman max 
mcgrath in london she must have been affected emotionally 
especially when demonstrators carried pictures of her father at the 
head of the procession 
in an interview with a british television network last week she 
said she had no plans for a new political party or an immediate 
blueprint for a future burma beyond an interim peoples 
consultative committee leading to democracy 
if her program sounded vague her presence stirred strong 
emotions 
its like if george washingtons son had come along in 1830 
and said id like to be president of the united stats it would 
have a certain ring to it says british burma expert robert h 
taylor 
like washington whose name aung san used to invoke the burmese 
leader fought for independence from britain sealing their vow to 
liberate burma in blood he and the socalled thirty comrades 
marched into their homeland during world war ii attacking first 
the allies and then the japanese 
contemporaries recall aung san as a compelling personality a 
sincere highly principled and simpleliving man who could mix 
easily with colleagues and then lapse into periods of brooding 
silence 
after the war he negotiated successfully with the british 
government for independence but months before it was granted the 
youthful handsome aung san and half a dozen other leaders were 
killed when assassins of a political opponent burst into a cabinet 
meeting with automatic rifles blazing his death on july 19 1947 
is still commemorated as martyrs day 
aung san suu kyi was barely 2 years old when her father died 
she was educated in burma and india where he mother served as 
ambassador from 1960 to 1967 
she obtained a bachelor of arts degree from oxford university in 
1967 worked at the united nations headquarters in new york and in 
1972 married michael aris an oxford professor and expert on 
tibetan culture and the himalayan region 
although she accompanied her husband on long research stints to 
bhutan nepal japan and other asian countries acquaintances say 
she did not pursue a career after marriage 
the demonstrations against a quarter century of oppressive rule 
ended the calm of her private life some burmese also called for 
the return of her brother aung san oo a 45yearold american 
citizen living in the united states 
despite the rousing welcome for aung san suu kyi i think 
people are beginning to have some questions about her said a 
western diplomat in rangoon shes really an expatriate with no 
political experience 
but in a bbc interview she countered this by saying i have 
never been away in my thoughts i have never been away from my 
country and my people in my heart also i have never been 
seperated from them 
she and her husband who is with her in rangoon along with their 
two sons regularly visited burma during the ne win period rather 
than an emigre opposition figure she was allowed to return home at 
the price of keeping an apolitical silence about conditions in her 
country burmese emigres say 
some burmese believe her marriage to a foreigner would not be 
well accepted by many in the inwardlooking nation 
it also is unclear whether she has any formal political 
ambitions although last week she appeared to be thinking about a 
future in burma 
the burmese people love my father very much and i think they 
are ready to support me because im my fathers daughter she 
said 
</TEXT>
