<TEXT>
days before he was shot to 
death in january 16yearold rabeh mahmoud told his family he 
wanted to give his life for the palestinian cause his sister 
sabah recalls 
mahmoud is one of 53 youths under age 18 who have been kille 
during the 8monthold palestinian uprising in the occupied west 
bank and gaza strip they comprise about a fourth of the deaths 
from israeli army gunfire thousands of other youths have been 
wounded 
tv viewers worldwide have seen the young palestinian boys in 
kafiyeh headdresses throwing rocks at troops then running as 
soldiers respond with tear gas and bullets 
israeli military officials allege the youths are placed in the 
front lines of protests to generate world sympathy and portray 
israeli occupation troops as ruthless soldiers who do not hesitate 
to shoot children 
children are weapons in this war it is very sinister said 
col renaan gissin the armys deputy spokesman 
with children up front they palestinian leaders win either 
way whether our soldiers refrain from shooting because of strict 
orders to avoid hurting children or if they open fire the 
palestinians win the war for the media gissin said they make 
sure the picture of the dead child makes it to the papers 
but the youngsters encountered in refugee camps throwing rocks 
at soldiers not much older than themselves say they are the 
leaders of the revolt 
they have become known as the children of the stones after a 
poem by syrian writer nizar qabani the palestine liberation 
organization has made posters of youngsters holding firebombs 
palestinians call children who are killed martyrs not 
victims 
sabah mahmoud the sister of slain 16yearold rabeh says her 
father now is worried about about his 13yearold son who is often 
out in the streets with friends the father cries whenever soldiers 
pass their house she said 
when rabeh told my father he wanted to die for palestine we 
thought he was joking sabah said sitting below a goldframed 
portrait of her dead brother the only picture on the walls of the 
beitin village farmhouse not far from ramallah 
united nations casualty lists updated as of aug 12 show 202 
palestinians killed by israeli army gunfire of these 53 are 18 or 
younger with 18 under 16 years old and six who were below 14 
the youngest casualty listed by the un was a 9yearold girl 
but the army said she was killed by a rock thrown by a palestinian 
the army whose death figures differ only slightly from un ones 
does not give breakdowns by age 
the un count shows three other arab youths under 18 including 
a 12yearold were shot to death by jewish settlers a 14 and 
17yearold were beaten to death by troops the un says 
an official of an international relief organization speaking on 
conditoin of anonymity estimated at least 8000 youngster have 
been wounded by bullets beatings tear gas or rubber bullets 
israeli youths arent directly involved in the protests but 
they are among civilians injured by rocks and firebombs hurled at 
cars the army lists 312 such casualties but has no breakdown by 
age 
a jewish girl 15yearold tirza porat was shot to death 
accidentally by an armed escort in the west bank in april when a 
group of jewish hikers clashed with arab villagers police are 
investigating whether an 8yearold boy slain august 27 near haifa 
was killed by palestinians 
one reason palestinian youngsters are so involved in protests is 
demographic almost 50 percent of the population of the occupied 
territories is 17 or younger according to the west bank data 
project research foundation 
these are youngsters raised under the military rule israel has 
maintained over the west bank and gaza strip since the territories 
were captured from jordan and egypt in 1967 
analysts say the young have become radicalized and are rebelling 
against israel and the traditional leadership of their elders 
which failed to secure an independent state 
its a schoolyard revolution said bernard mills a un 
relief works agency official in the occupied gaza strip even 
before the uprising by march of 1987 if you were over 14 years 
old and hadnt been arrested by the israelis you hadnt got your 
school letter to put it in american terms 
young people 18 to 25 are emerging as the new generation of 
leaders and their younger siblings are followers and wouldbe 
successors military sources said 
like the americans of the 1960s who said dont trust anyone 
over 30 they are saying dont trust anyone over 25 gissin 
said 
the israeli army recently introduced plastic bullets in a move 
it says is intended to cut casualties the army says its soldiers 
have orders not to open fire at children but occupation rules 
consider those over age 14 accountable for their actions 
chris george an official of save the children an american 
relief organization said the army should respect childrens status 
as minors 
even if a kid is involved in a confrontation throwing a rock 
for example there is no justification for a wellequipped army to 
use lethal force george said 
