<TEXT>
the parents of a high school student 
convicted of murdering his classmate have decided not to take part 
in a movie about the slaying spurning a 35000 offer that will go 
to the victims mother a newspaper reported 
the movie will be dedicated to the memory of shaun ouillette 
who was a 15yearold freshman at canton high school when he was 
beaten to death with a baseball bat in 1986 said dennis bogorad of 
dave bell associates a hollywoodbased production company 
rod matthews also 15 was convicted in march of seconddegree 
murder in the slaying of his classmate 
they matthews parents have no interest in the movie a 
family friend mel ginsberg told the patriot ledger of quincy 
theyre not going to make it they didnt sign anything mr and 
mrs matthews are not out to capitalize on this 
theyre just an average family and they dont want any more 
damage done ginsberg said 
he said the matthews were upset when ouillettes mother jeanne 
quinn accused them on geraldo riveras national television talk 
show of accepting blood money and trying to capitalize on the 
crime 
kenneth and janice matthews had planned to donate a 35000 
payment from the movie production company plus a share of the 
profits to a psychiatric clinic where their son was held prior to 
his trial in march the newspaper reported thursday 
the family decided to forego the fee when it learned that 
ouillettes estate could sue to obtain the profits within three 
years 
quinn said she has agreed to help make the movie and will 
receive the 35000 payment she has said she is participating to 
guarantee events surrounding her sons death are accurately 
portrayed 
matthews was sentenced to life in prison and is eligible for 
parole in 2001 
