<TEXT>
a federal judge has dismissed two 
multibilliondollar lawsuits filed against morton thiokol by a 
former engineer who warned against the disastrous launch of the 
space shuttle challenger a lawyer said thursday 
robert levin attorney for former rocket engineer roger 
boisjoly told ksltv that he learned thursday afternoon that us 
district judge david k winder had dismissed the 3 billion suits 
with prejudice meaning they cannot be refiled 
court documents were expected to be made public friday morning 
the judge had taken the matter under advisement in february 
following a hearing on the companys motion to quash the suits 
one of boisjolys suits had sought 1 billion for the deaths of 
the seven challenger crew members on jan 28 1986 and 1 million 
in compensatory damages for his own health and career 
boisjoly who this year won the scientific freedom and 
responsibility award from the american association for the 
advancement of science contended morton thiokol impugned his 
professional reputation after he and other engineers testified 
before a presidential commission investigating the challenger 
explosion the engineers testified that they had warned against 
launching the shuttle in the unusually cool weather 
his other lawsuit filed under the false claims act on behalf of 
us taxpayers sought 2075 billion and alleged that morton 
thiokol knowingly provided the national aeronautics and space 
administration with defective solid rocket motors 
morton thiokol spokesman rocky raab said the company had 
received no official notification of the decision 
but if in fact it does prove to be true it does vindicate 
what weve said all along it repudiates what the claims were about 
challenger that he boisjoly made he said 
most of all were just glad to see that its over with 
raab said 
company attorneys had said boisjolys assertion that he was 
defamed was based on office chatter 
it is just workplacerelated talk that goes on all the time 
attorney robert jordan told the judge during februarys hearing 
however levin accused company officials of having launched a 
campaign to defame the engineer through pamphlets and interviews 
not coffeeshop stuff 
in a may interview boisjoly said only after two years of 
therapy and the positive catharsis of giving lectures on the 
disaster was he able to stop blaming himself for the destruction of 
the shuttle and deaths of the astronauts 
boisjoly and several other morton thiokol engineers had argued 
the night before the launch that temperatures of 53 degrees 
fahrenheit or less could result in a failure of a rocket joint seal 
but after a second caucus with nasa officials boisjoly said 
company managers perceived pressure from nasa there was no 
other justification for the launch i felt the pressure others 
felt the pressure 
he took disability leave july 21 1986 and left the company for 
good two months later 
the rogers commission investigating the explosion later blamed 
the disaster on a leaking joint seal that allowed superhot gases to 
escape and ignite the shuttles external fuel tank 
</TEXT>
