<TEXT>
investigators thursday found the flap 
indicator handle on a shattered boeing 727 in the wrong position 
but a federal safety official said it could have been jarred that 
way in the fiery crash which killed 13 people 
the handle which is located on the console between the pilot 
and the first officer indicates the position of the aircrafts 
wing flaps 
at a news conference thursday night national transportation 
safety board member lee dickinson said the handle on the delta air 
lines jet that crashed wednesday was found to be in the up 
position opposite where it should have been for a proper takeoff 
but he went on to say the handle could have been pushed into the 
wrong position by the impact or by a crew member during the planes 
evacuation 
delta flight 1141 went down as it tried to take off from 
dallasfort worth international airport en route to salt lake city 
with more than 100 people aboard most were able to escape the 
burning plane by crawling out of emergency exits or tornopen areas 
all 13 deaths were attributed to smoke inhalation according to 
the tarrant county medical examiners office with burns also 
listed in two instances 
one of the survivors robert coester 39 of the dallas suburb 
of carrollton said he was most troubled by his unsuccessful 
efforts to rescue passengers trapped in the back of the burning 
plane 
i tried to get the rear door open said coester who was 
hospitalized for smoke inhalation and first second and 
thirddegree burns there was a handle on the outside i got the 
door ajar but not enough for them to get out 
investigators found at least five bodies near that door after 
the flames were extinguished 
the same flight thursday from dallasfort worth to salt lake 
city was aborted when the pilot detected a problem with his plane 
most of the 102 passengers including six survivors of the crash 
wednesday left about two hours later on another plane delta 
officials said 
federal investigators determined that the flaps and slats aboard 
a northwest airlines md80 had not been properly set for takeoff 
when that plane crashed aug 16 1987 at detroit metropolitan 
airport killing 156 people 
dickinson cautioned that the ntsb investigation team had just 
begun to study positions of the delta aircrafts wings and slats 
ntsb investigators said none of the witnesses they interviewed 
who were on nearby planes could tell them the position of the 
airplanes flaps 
dickinson said investigators have not talked to the crew but 
hoped to interview first officer wilson kirkland on friday 
the ntsb official also said control tower personnel indicated 
the boeing 727 took off at an angle that was higher than normal 
control tower workers who watched the plane leaving told 
investigators the plane had a nose high attitude of 15 to 20 
degrees 
investigators assume that they meant that was higher than 
normal dickinson said 
earlier thursday dickinson told reporters the planes crew had 
another indication of trouble during takeoff a cockpit tape 
recording recovered from the plane showed that pilots had talked 
about an engine problem seconds before the jetliner crashed 
shortly after takeoff there was a sound apparently a 
warning a stall condition may be approaching dickinson said he 
said the sound came from the shaking of the stick a device 
similar to the steering wheel that automatically makes a sound when 
a problem develops 
this indicates the plane may be approaching a point where it 
wont be able to fly he said shortly after that there was 
some conversation about an engine problem 
but he stressed that the warning sound could have stemmed from 
something besides an engine problem he would not elaborate except 
to say in this case were talking about hydraulics 
every accident in its own way is unique said ntsb spokesman 
michael benson you have to start from the beginning put 
together a mosaic and slowly discover what went wrong 
on wednesday the 15yearold boeing 727 failed to gain 
sufficient altitude bounced three times on the runway and burst 
into flames 
at least 95 people aboard miraculously survived by clambering or 
being pulled through emergency doors or through cracks in the 
burning fuselage into the hazy sunshine 
why why did it happen thats the question we have to answer 
now delta spokesman bill berry said in atlanta deltas 
headquarters 
witnesses said there appeared to have been a fire or explosion 
in an engine on takeoff federal aviation administration spokesman 
jack barker said 
but that was not confirmed he said this was merely what 
some witnesses were reporting 
thirty to 40 investigators from the ntsb delta boeing and 
pratt amp whitney which manufactured the planes three engines 
fanned out over an area about the size of two football fields 
examining pieces of the wrecked aircraft 
wearing gloves and carrying bags some crawled inside the 
charred hulk using the same cracks where passengers braved flaming 
jet fuel 24 hours earlier they also climbed on the lone remaining 
attached wing which had been turned redhot by the fire to peer 
into the cabin through blackened windows at one point about 20 of 
them gathered peering intently at the left rear engine they 
removed the engine shroud and looked inside 
the cockpit recording as well as the planes flight data 
recorder had already been recovered in good condition from the 
wreckage and taken to washington for analysis 
dickinson said safety board officials had listened to the 
cockpit tape recording just once and they and other investigators 
planned to listen to again 
the pilot capt larry davis 48 of greenville was pinned in 
the wreckage and had to be extricated by rescuers he was listed in 
fair condition thursday at parkland hospital in dallas suffering 
back injuries and burns 
davis has been a delta pilot since 1965 and a boeing 727 captain 
for nine years 
his copilot and engineer also survived the accident but two 
delta flight attendants were among the 13 fatalities all of the 
dead were from texas 
ninetyseven passengers and a crew of seven were listed aboard 
the aircraft but the exact count was uncertain because babies were 
not included on passenger lists 
three years ago a delta l1011 crashed at the same airport 
killing 137 in the worst aviation accident in texas history 
delta spokesman henry conley said none of the airlines other 
727s would be pulled from service because of wednesdays crash 
we dont see anything serious enough to pull any planes he 
said 
