<TEXT>
the government imposed more than 1 million in 
fines on 32 airlines for faulty airport security procedures as part 
of a stepped up effort to improve passenger screening 
the fines announced thursday by the federal aviation 
administration range from 1000 against a number smaller mainly 
commuter airlines to 215000 against united airlines 156000 
against northwest airlines and 113000 against delta air lines 
while the passenger screening at airport checkpoints usually is 
conducted by private security companies the airlines hire the 
companies and are responsible for the program 
the fines stem from faa tests conducted at major airports 
nationwide in which agency inspectors carried phony weapons through 
airport security checkpoints without being detected the faa said 
faa administrator allan mcartor said a recent audit of the 
security tests conducted by the faa showed improved screening but 
nearly 15 percent of the phony weapons still passed through 
undetected 
the 856 percent detection rate during the first six months of 
the year compares with a 789 percent rate during all of 1987 
mcartor said he added that some airport checkpoints detected more 
than 95 percent of the weapons in the faa tests he said 
but mcartor said that while the improvement in the detection 
rate is encouraging tough enforcement measures including civil 
penalties are needed to insure industrywide improvements and 
systemwide safety 
security lapses at airport checkpoints became a focus of 
attention last year when a congressional report chastized the faa 
for the screening systems shortcomings 
the subject gained additional attention after a disgruntled 
former usair employee smuggled a weapon aboard a pacific southwest 
airlines jet and began shooting causing the plane to crash all 43 
people aboard the plane which was flying from los angeles to san 
francisco were killed 
after the incident the faa announced it was using special teams 
of investigators to test security at 16 major airports last march 
transportation secretary jim burnley said the tests would improve 
the effectiveness of the screening programs 
we want to see a 100 percent success rate in detecting weapons 
and dummy weapons burnley said in a statement thursday he 
promised to continue the airport tests 
mcartor meanwhile indicated that the faa may seek additional 
fines in the future if lapses are uncovered we have no choice 
but to take tough enforcement action in those instances where 
security lapses are discovered he said 
