<TEXT>
a federal appeals court upheld the 
espionage convictions and 365year prison sentence of exnavy 
radioman jerry whitworth a member of the walker spy ring that 
passed military secrets to the soviets 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals ruled 30 thursday that 
the punishment fit whitworths crime of selling ultrasensitive 
navy decoding and communications information to the soviet union 
the sentence imposed by us district judge john vukasin 
viewed in the abstract would appear harsh the court said 
this sentence however is not disproportionate to whitworths 
crimes 
whitworth 49 of davis calif a radioman with a topsecret 
clearance for much of his 18year navy career was convicted in 
1986 of seven counts of espionage for supplying ultrasensitive 
decoding and communications information to spymaster john walker 
for nearly a decade in exchange for 332000 
vukasin called whitworth one of the most spectacular spies of 
the century and imposed the nations harshest sentence for 
espionage since julius and ethel rosenberg convicted of conspiring 
to furnish atomic bomb secrets to the soviets were electrocuted in 
1953 
whitworths sentence forbids parole consideration for 60 years 
in the decision the court rejected defense arguments that a 
sentence longer than walkers amounted to cruel and unusual 
punishment 
military and intelligence officials testified at the trial that 
the spy ring had revealed the navys most precious secrets and 
caused damage that may be impossible to calculate 
walker also recruited his son and brother as members of the spy 
ring he pleaded guilty in a baltimore federal court to spying for 
the soviets for 17 years and was sentenced to life in prison with 
parole possible in 10 years 
the opinion by judge robert boochever said the us constitution 
does not require a judge in one court to compare a defendants 
relative guilt to that of a defendant in another court on separate 
charges before imposing sentence 
even if comparison of guilt was required boochever said the 
court notes that whitworth kept walkers espionage operation alive 
for nearly a decade and himself became a central figure because of 
his access to highly classified material 
whitworths chief prosecutor former assistant us attorney 
william farmer commented the sentence was not harsh at all if 
this had been a case where there was a death penalty available it 
clearly would have been prosecuted as a capital case 
assistant us attorney sanford svetcov who represented the 
prosecution on appeal agreed that whitworth deserved a death 
sentence which was abolished for espionage and other federal 
crimes by a 1972 supreme court ruling 
its a sickness in our society that we have people willing to 
do harm to their own country for money svetcov said these 
guys were not communists by any means they were strictly in it for 
profit 
whitworths lawyer on appeal alan caplan said he was 
disappointed by the ruling and would appeal he said he was 
astounded by the courts conclusion that the verdict was not 
influenced when walker was improperly allowed to speculate on the 
witness stand that whitworth must have known the secrets were being 
delivered to the soviet union 
walker also a former navy radioman with a topsecret clearance 
testified that he had started selling secrets to a soviet agent in 
1968 and recruited whitworth as his chief supplier of classified 
materials in 1974 after walker himself no longer had direct access 
to the material 
whitworth was convicted of furnishing to walker the secrets of 
navy decoding equipment code keys and communications systems that 
whitworth gathered and photographed for nearly a decade as a highly 
placed radio officer at ship and shore stations 
