<TEXT>
defense secretary frank carlucci warned 
congress not to act hastily to change the way it reviews defense 
spending in the wake of a major fraud probe involving defense 
contractors and consultants 
lawmakers should not adopt reform proposals being circulated on 
capitol hill including creation of an independent acquisition 
agency removing the inspector general from the department of 
defense and locking the revolving door between the dod and 
defense contractors carlucci said on thursday 
certainly we want to see those found guilty of wrongdoing 
punished and punished severely for their actions but reform 
is really about prevention not punishment carlucci said 
the speech before the baltimore council on foreign affairs was 
the most comprehensive statement to date by the secretary since 
revelations of a widespread investigation of alleged fraud 
involving defense contractors and consultants 
in his prescription for procurement reform carlucci called 
on congress to simplify its budgetmaking process reduce the 
number of committees that oversee defense spending shift the 
pentagon budget to a twoyear cycle and provide multiyear funding 
for more weapon programs 
the goal should be to limit the number of intervention points 
where a skillful lobbyist can succeed in gaining an advantage he 
said 
right now the defense budget bill must complete a 17step 
process to final passage carlucci said each point along the 
way is an opportunity for those bent on exerting improper 
influence 
congress must seek ways to reduce the profusion of 
intervention points on capitol hill that invite improper if not 
always strictly illegal behavior he said 
however rep les aspin dwis chairman of the house armed 
services committee said the speech failed to address central 
issues of procurement 
since the procurement scandal erupted we have seen people 
selling old ideas that have nothing to do with the procurement 
problem aspin said they are pet rocks dressed up as solutions 
to the scandal but they are still pet rocks i am afraid secretary 
carlucci has fallen into the same trap in his speech billed 
prescription for procurement reform 
his proposal dealt with budget reform not procurement reform 
his suggestions say nothing about the use of consultants the abuse 
of insider information or restoration of the integrity of the 
bidding process the congressman said 
many of his suggestions for budget reform are valid and have 
been pushed by me and others over the years but they have nothing 
to do with procurement reform aspin said 
the justice department investigation which became public in 
june centers on allegations that defense contractors routinely 
used outside consultants to obtain proprietary information on the 
bids of competitors and that the consultants may have paid bribes 
to pentagon employees 
carlucci warned against a legislative rush to enact reforms 
without considering their effects 
at the very least dods critics owe us a hearing before they 
try to pass legislation that could impact our procurement process 
and the defense industrial base for years to come he said 
we need to ask how does the system as it exists today offer 
wrongdoers the opportunity to act and how can we close these 
windows of vulnerability in the procurement process 
carlucci said establishment of an independent acquisition agency 
by congress would erect barriers between the acquisition process 
and those in the pentagon who know best what weapons they need 
likewise the defense department relies on the revolving 
door that brings experts from the industry into government 
carlucci said 
we need to police the system for abuses not penalize 
procurement professionals for seeking to build on and benefit from 
their expertise he said 
