<TEXT>
feuding black political 
organizations today signed an agreement aimed at ending the 
countrys bloodiest ongoing conflict in which more than 600 people 
have died in 20 months 
the fighting in natal province has pitted supporters of militant 
antiapartheid organizations against members of inkatha a more 
conservative group headed by prominent zulu leader mangosuthu 
buthelezi 
inkathas secretary general oscar dhlomo and jay naidoo 
secretary general of the militant congress of south african trade 
unions signed the agreement at a courthouse in the provincial 
capital pietermaritzburg 
the labor federation known as cosatu has been allied with the 
united democratic front a nowbanned antiapartheid coalition in 
the feud against inkatha 
the agreement condemns violence and calls for formation of a 
conciliation board which would review residents complaints of 
harassment or attacks the boards members would be selected 
jointly by the two sides and have disciplinary powers 
as part of the agreement each side will drop pending court 
cases accusing the other of violence 
each party recognizes the immediate necessity to make it 
abundantly clear to its members that coastu and inkatha 
categorically condemn acts of intimidation forced recruitment and 
violence the agreement says 
all political organizations have the right to exist and the 
democratic right to espouse their own particular viewpoint it 
says 
most of the fighting has been in the black townships around 
pietermaritzburg but has spread in recent months to townships near 
the larger port city of durban many of the killings have been to 
avenge earlier killings 
both inkatha which claims 15 million members and the united 
democratic frontcosatu alliance oppose the apartheid policies 
which enable south africas 5 million whites to dominate 26 million 
blacks but their strategies differ markedly 
the front a predominantly black coalition of about 600 groups 
advocates economic sanctions strikes and other confrontational 
measures to bring about sweeping political and economic change 
inkatha opposes sanctions avoids militant protest and advocates 
capitalism 
many militants view buthelezi as a government collaborator 
because he is chief minister of the kwazulu homeland however 
buthelezi has rejected invitations by the government to join in 
negotiating reforms that would expand blacks political role while 
leaving whites in ultimate control 
peter kerschoff a social worker in pietermaritzburg who has 
been involved in past reconciliation efforts said the agreement 
was an important but not final step toward ending the conflict 
because of government bans and restrictions it is extremely 
difficult for cosatu and the udf to communicate with grassroots 
people this will have to be addressed he said in a telephone 
interview 
the natal violence has distressed other antiapartheid 
campaigners and caused debate over whether black political groups 
could avoid factional fights and effectively oppose the whiteled 
government 
some commentators viewed the conflict as a harbinger of 
widespread black infighting that might develop as black groups with 
different ideologies struggled for supremacy 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

