<TEXT>
the soviets are expanding naval facilities in 
the syrian port of tartus and the neighboring island of arwad to 
counter the us presence in the mediterranean israeli analysts 
said friday 
soviet installations in tartus including submarine and surface 
ship maintenance facilities constitute the largest soviet naval 
base in the mediterranean said dore gold of tel aviv universitys 
jaffee center for strategic studies 
aharon levran editor of the middle east military balance 
published this week by the center said the facilities extend to 
arwad island and include recreation facilities for soviet crews 
gold said no declassified information was available on the 
current or planned size of the soviet base but that the general 
and continuing trend has been expansion since 1987 
he said the soviet navys mediterranean squadron is using 
tartus about 200 miles north of tel aviv because it is outside 
soviet territory and has good access to the mediterranean 
the soviets use other land installations in syria for 
intelligencegathering gold and levran said in separate interviews 
gold said the main objective of the tartus base expansion was to 
counter the us 6th fleet presence in the mediterranean 
the united states has bases in spain italy greece and france 
the soviet union had to find new arrangements after albania shifted 
its alliance to china in 1961 and egypt dropped its friendship 
treaty with moscow in 1976 he said 
gold said the tartus facility was important for prolonged 
deployment of soviet attack submarines in the mediterranean 
the londonbased janes defense weekly in may called tartus 
the primary maintenance facility for soviet submarines operating 
in the mediterranean 
levran said the soviets have been using tartus for at least five 
years and that the bases expansion apparently was a price syria 
had to pay for purchasing soviet weapons 
despite the kremlins recent reluctance to supply syria with 
advanced weapons systems he said syria is still the soviet 
unions strategic asset in the middle east 
he said the base replaced the soviet practice of using 
mediterranean squadron ships for maintenance but he said the base 
was less important than the recently developed soviet far eastern 
base in cam ranh bay vietnam 
