<TEXT>
saturdays election in singapore will pass the 
torch of leadership to a younger generation but the man who has 
led this prosperous asian citystate since 1959 is not expected to 
retire 
the governing peoples action party is expected to win the 
parliamentary election by a big margin prime minister lee kuan 
yew who will be 65 on sept 16 is expected to step down in favor 
of first deputy prime minister goh chok tong 46 
lee who called the election truly a watershed has been 
prime minister since 1959 and more than half of the 26 million 
people have known no other leader 
he is to remain secretarygeneral of the pap and although he 
has expressed disinterest is still regarded as the most logical 
candidate to be the countrys first elected president 
those who believe that when i have left the government as 
prime minister that i have gone into permanent retirement really 
should have their heads examined lee said recently 
the proposed elected presidency remained the key issue as the 
nineday campaign wound down friday it would replace the current 
appointed ceremonial post with a president holding veto power over 
spending the nations ample financial reserves and nominations to 
senior civil service and judicial positions 
even the most optimistic of opposition leaders do not expect to 
be able to muster enough votes to form a government 
the singapore democratic party under chaim see tong the only 
opposition member when the last parliament was dissolved would 
settle for denying the pap the twothirds majority needed to amend 
the constitution save democracy now deny them twothirds is 
the slogan for the partys 18 candidates 
the biggest opposition challenge was posed by the workers 
party which fielded 32 candidates but secretarygeneral jb 
jeyaretnam who won election with chaim at the last polls in 1984 
was disqualified from parliament for five years from 1986 for 
falsifying party accounts 
the pap won 77 of the 79 seats in 1984 but was shocked by a 126 
percent drop in total popular vote to 629 percent the opposition 
gain was attributed to several issues including a proposal to bar 
the withdrawal of savings from the central provident fund a 
mandatory social securitylike program at age 55 
senior party officials now make regular walkabouts to press 
the flesh and sample public opinion controversial proposals such 
as the elected presidency are no longer rammed through parliament 
on the strength of a twothirds majority 
the party has tried to lure voters by promising welfare 
recipients more money and recommending wage increases after two 
years of official restraint caused by recession 
parents were told they may use central provident fund savings to 
finance college educations for their children the national day 
celebrations this month were made extra festive with a 
governmentsanctioned street party that attracted 250000 revelers 
more good years is the pap slogan the party takes credit 
for a booming economy that generated 112 percent growth in 
inflationadjusted terms in the first half of the year 
singaporeans enjoy one of the highest living standards in asia 
and 86 percent of them live in apartments built by a government 
that is is generally perceived to be efficient and relatively free 
of corruption 
the recently enlarged unicameral parliament now has 81 seats 
and the legislators serve fiveyear terms the pap already has 11 
seats where it was running unopposed 
the pap needs to win at least 30 more seats to get a simple 
majority of 41 to form a new government and run the country for the 
eighth consecutive term since 1959 
it faces 141 candidates from seven opposition parties and four 
independents opposition candidates numbered only 51 in the last 
election 
there are 42 traditional singlemember voting districts but for 
the first time each party competing in 13 constituencies had to 
nominate three candidates at least one of them from a minority 
group voters select a team of three and each gets a separate vote 
in parliament 
singapores 2 million people are 76 percent ethnic chinese 
about 15 percent malay and six percent indians 
voting is compulsory for the 15 million eligible voters in the 
70 contested districts voting hours saturday are from 8 am to 8 
pm with results expected about midnight 
