<TEXT>
scrawling your john hancock across the back of a 
paycheck may not be enough to get it cashed anymore no matter how 
large your bank account or how well you know your teller 
a new federal law guaranteeing customers faster access to their 
deposits includes littleknown uniform standards for endorsing 
checks 
under the regulations which took effect thursday all 
endorsements must be within a 1inch section along the edge of the 
back of the check so they dont interfere with endorsements from 
the bank at which the check is deposited 
only appropriate color ink such as blue and black may be 
used by banks for their endorsements according to the regulations 
administered by the federal reserve board 
financial institutions say they have been training employees and 
mailing out brochures with diagrams to educate customers on the new 
standards 
robert hutchinson a senior vice president from manufacturers 
hanover trust in new york said there have been few problems so far 
im unaware of any excessive long lines he said but 
lets be honest theres going to be an adjustment period its 
going to take time for everyone to understand and adjust to the 
rules 
some bank employees said privately they were bracing for a few 
initial headaches 
incorrect customer endorsements they said could delay check 
clearing and might affect subsequent transactions based on money 
derived from that check 
it wont be the banks problem its the customers problem 
but well be hearing about it said one branch manager of a large 
new yorkbased bank 
stores also have had to adjust to the new guidelines many 
businesses routinely stamp the backs of checks with a lengthy list 
of identification items store clerks must obtain from customers 
as a result stores have had to buy new rubber stamps or 
reprogram cash registers to print within the smaller endorsement 
area 
the fed has defended the new requirements as necessary to speed 
checkclearing so that bounced checks can be returned quickly to 
the institution where they were cashed 
the new rules require financial institutions to give customers 
access to deposited funds within one three or seven days 
depending on the type of check 
consumer groups had complained that too many banks were holding 
funds for periods as long as two or three weeks before making the 
money available to the depositor a practice that cost americans 
millions of dollars in interest 
</TEXT>
