<DOCNO> AP880902-0153 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the first big radio telescope array 
in the southern hemisphere began operating friday opening a new 
window on the littleexplored southern sky 
well be looking at the center of our galaxy because it passes 
right above our head in the southern hemisphere said dr ron 
ekers the director of the instrument named the australia 
telescope much of the galaxy and the nearest neighboring galaxy 
the magellanic cloud is not visible to observatories in the 
northern hemisphere 
ekers who for seven years was director of the 27dish very 
large array radio telescope in western new mexico said the 
telescope will study black holes and pulsars 
the new 40 million instrument located on the windswept plains 
of western new south wales consists of five new 726foot dishes 
mounted on 186 miles of railroad track 
an identical dish on a track 186 miles away will make the array 
equivalent to one dish with a diameter 372 miles 
when linked to the exisiting 211footdish at parkes 241 miles 
to the south and others spread across the continent the australia 
telescope can be extended like a zoom lens on a camera to the 
equivalent of a dish 2400 miles in diameter 
the commonwealth scientific and industrial organization the 
government funded research institution that designed the 
telescope said the compact array of seven telescopes had an 
equivalent resolution to being able to read a telephone directory 
at a distance of 660 feet 
when linked to telescopes in space it would be 10000 times 
greater 
the australia telescope is the state of the art in 
astronomical technology it is one of the best telescopes in the 
world prime minister bob hawke told an audience of astronomers 
and scientists at the inaugural ceremony 
harry van der laan head of the european southern observatory in 
chile said if australia hadnt built it the european southern 
observatory would have had to do it in chile 
we have the biggest optical telescopes in the southern 
hemisphere at la silla in chile but we had no major radio 
telescope array world astronomy cannot do without it he said 
this fills that gap and it puts australia back in the top 
league of astronomy its the equivalent of winning the americas 
cup in yachting van der laan said 
</TEXT>
