<TEXT>
rival black political groups 
signed an accord friday to end what has been called the countrys 
worst factional fighting this century in which more than 600 people 
have been killed in 20 months 
an explosion rocked downtown durban just after the evening rush 
hour causing extensive damage to a clothing store and slightly 
injuring a black woman police said 
in other cities a hand grenade was tossed at the home of south 
africas leading mixedrace politician and a bomb exploded in a 
post office no injuries were reported in either attack 
the agreement signed friday sought to halt savage fighting in 
the natal province between supporters of militant antiapartheid 
organizations and members of inkatha a more conservative group 
headed by zulu leader mangosuthu buthelezi 
it was signed at a courthouse in the provincial capital 
pietermaritzburg by inkathas secretarygeneral oscar dhlomo and 
by jay naidoo secretary general of the militant congress of south 
african trade unions 
the labor federation has been allied with the united democratic 
front a nowbanned antiapartheid coalition in the feud against 
inkatha 
the agreement condemns violence and establishes an adjudication 
board to review complaints of harassment or attacks the boards 
members would be selected jointly by the two sides and would have 
disciplinary powers 
each party recognizes the immediate necessity to make it 
abundantly clear to its members that cosatu and inkatha 
categorically condemn acts of intimidation forced recruitment and 
violence the agreement says all political organizations have 
the right to exist and the democratic right to espouse their own 
particular viewpoint 
nicholas haysom a lawyer for the labor federation who helped 
draft the accord said both sides were cautious about their ability 
to convince rankandfile supporters to honor the pact 
the level of retribution and atrocious violence has made 
conditions almost impossible to exercise freedom of association 
he said 
haysom said the adjudication board will be able to judge cases 
far more quickly than the courts can and will seek to gain the 
confidence of witnesses who have been fearful of making statements 
to police 
supreme court justice ns page who had asked the two sides to 
pursue an accord said the courts were not abdicating their 
responsibilities but viewed the new board as a valuable additional 
tool to help stop the bloodshed 
most of the fighting has been in black townships around 
pietermaritzburg although it has spread in recent months to 
townships near the larger port city of durban many of the killings 
have been to avenge earlier killings 
both inkatha which claims 15 million members and the united 
democratic frontlabor federation alliance oppose the apartheid 
policies which enable 5 million whites to dominate 26 million 
blacks but their strategies differ markedly 
the united democratic front a predominantly black coalition of 
some 600 groups advocates economic sanctions strikes and other 
confrontational measures to bring about sweeping political and 
economic change 
inkatha opposes sanctions avoids militant protest and advocates 
capitalism 
many militants view buthelezi as a government collaborator 
because he is chief minister of the kwazulu homeland however 
buthelezi has rejected invitations by the government to join in 
negotiating reforms that would expand blacks political role while 
leaving whites in ultimate control 
peter kerschoff a social worker in pietermaritzburg who has 
been involved in past reconciliation efforts said the agreement 
was not the final step toward peace 
because of government bans and restrictions he said in a 
telephone interview it is extremely difficult for cosatu and the 
udf to communicate with grassroots people this will have to be 
addressed 
the natal violence has distressed antiapartheid campaigners 
elsewhere in south africa and sparked debate over whether black 
political groups could unite effectively to oppose the whiteled 
government 
some commentators viewed the conflict as a harbinger of 
widespread infighting that might develop as black groups with 
different ideologies struggled for supremacy 
</TEXT>
