v bochkov writing in the newspaper sovietskaya rossiya said 
many specialists estimate the deficit as equal to 15 percent to 17 
percent of state revenues 
the economist did not give a specific figure but said the 
soviet deficit was many billions of rubles an amount he said 
was nearly half of what is being spent to meet the countrys social 
and cultural needs 
the communist partys policymaking central committee in a july 
plenary meeting said that when next years state budget and 
economic plan are drawn up it will be necessary to take decisive 
steps to cut the deficit 
the 1988 government budget as approved by the supreme soviet 
parliament in october totals 773 billion in his article bochkov 
specifically noted 66 billion in unforeseen expenses or revenue 
shortfalls 
lower world prices for oil and oil products a major soviet 
export item have led to a 23 billion drop in foreign income 
slashes in the production of vodka and other alcoholic drinks 
a key measure in gorbachevs 3yearold antidrinking campaign 
have resulted in a 30 billion drop in state revenue from alcohol 
sales 
finally an additional 126 billion have been spent to cope 
with the aftermath of the 1986 nuclear reactor explosion and fire 
at the chernobyl power plant which sparked the evacuation of more 
than 130000 residents of the northern ukraine and southern 
byelorussia 
bochkov said that more than 70 percent of soviet national income 
is redistributed through the state budget in line with gorbachevs 
drive to make each sector of the soviet economy selfsufficient 
bochkov called for a decisive move to selffinancing 
however many soviet factories and enterprises are still far 
from being able to stand on their own feet and meet expenses 
through their own revenues and depend on periodic injections of 
government funds 
bochkov said soviet warehouses and store shelves are now clogged 
with 746 billion in goods that no one wants to buy and since the 
products remain unsold the state earns no revenue from them 
in his article the economist also issued an indirect call for 
slimmeddown defense spending saying as in any sector of the 
expenditure of budgetary resources in the military sector there is 
also the possibility of economy 
the soviet unions 1988 budget officially allocates 32 billion 
for defense but western analysts contend actual soviet military 
spending is many times that figure 
