the soviet union has bought an additional 
800000 metric tons of us corn for delivery during the 198889 
marketing year that began thursday the agriculture department said 
friday 
sale of 100000 tons of corn was announced a day earlier also 
for delivery in 198889 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and is equal to 394 bushels 
of corn or 367 bushels of wheat or soybeans the 900000 tons of 
corn would be about 355 million bushels 
corn prices have been averaging about 249 per bushel at the 
farm level meaning that the two sales could have a farm value of 
around 884 million 
there was no indication whether the new sales of corn would 
count under the current longterm grain supply agreement between 
the two countries or be carried forward separately in case a new 
pact is forthcoming 
the current fiveyear pact is set to expire sept 30 and 
negotiators are currently trying to work out a new one or at least 
an extension of the current agreement to take effect oct 1 
arthur k homann of the departments foreign agricultural 
service said it would be determined later how to count the latest 
corn sales depending on the actual shipping dates and whether 
there is a new agreement 
regardless the soviet union has already lived up to terms of 
the final year of the agreement which calls for the annual 
purchase of at least 9 million tons of us grain 
according to the agreement the annual purchases are supposed to 
include a minimum of 4 million tons each of wheat and corn the 
soviets have the option of buying the remaining 1 million tons as 
wheat corn or soybeans with every ton of beans counting as two 
tons of grain up to a maximum of 1 million tons of grain 
equivalent 
prior to this weeks sales the soviet union had purchased 905 
million tons of wheat and 517 million tons of corn for delivery in 
the fifth year of the agreement plus 830000 tons of soybeans and 
13 million tons of soybean meal 
