<TEXT>
oral roberts university has reduced 
scholarship funds available to medical students and eliminated 
salaries for graduates who serve as medical missionaries for the 
university 
the move is the latest modification in the medical missionary 
program that was the object of evangelist oral roberts widely 
publicized 1987 fundraising effort in which he claimed he might 
die if donors didnt come forward 
under the revised scholarship program firstyear medical 
students are no longer eligible for scholarship aid offered to 
those who plan to become missionaries 
other medical students who sign contracts promising to work as 
missionaries are to receive up to 20000 in scholarship aid while 
they are in school university officials said thursday previously 
participants were eligible for up to 24000 
in addition the students will no longer be eligible for 22000 
salaries after graduation when they do the missionary work 
in january 1987 donations to the medical missionary scholarship 
program were falling when roberts issued a nationwide plea for 8 
million he said if he did not raise the money by april 1 1987 
god would call me home to heaven 
although oral roberts officials announced the goal was met 
roberts discontinued the scholarship program a year later amid much 
criticism three months after that he reinstated it 
students who withdraw from the program may continue to attend 
oral roberts said dr larry edwards dean of the medical school 
but they have to pay back whatever has been given them in 
scholarship money 
the medical student scholarship program was begun as a pilot 
project for a few students in 1985 at the end of last semester 
105 students were receiving scholarships 
the school now has 168 medical students enrolled including 46 
firstyear students 
the firstyear students are not being offered scholarships 
edwards said because officials want to get to know them during 
this school year to make sure they are truly called to be 
missionaries before offering aid 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

