<TEXT>
the big whew from the stock market last 
friday came from evidence that inflationary pressures and 
therefore interest rate increases might possibly be easing 
as has happened a hundred times in the past wall street once 
again is mesmerized by inflation and interestrate possibilities 
and it reacts almost instantly to any news on the subject 
a high or rising level of interest rates is of special 
importance to the stock market for at least two reasons 
first it is generally agreed that the stock market collapse of 
last october was triggered at least in part by rates rising to 
levels that made debt securities more rewarding than stocks 
next high or rising interest rates become an important factor 
in the cost of doing business as well as a disincentive to market 
expansion at all levels from consumers to manufacturers 
another reason might be added the federal reserve board has 
been watching job figures for a clue to inflation strong job 
figures might convince it to raise rates a weaker job market would 
mean an easing of pressure 
after viewing the figures wall street concluded that the 
inflation threat might not be as bad as feared and that the fed 
would have less reason to push up interest rates 
but the the threat is not over and wall steet will continue to 
focus on borrowing costs and inflation wright investors service 
presents the case 
at current interestrate levels says wright which advises on 
billions of dollars of investment funds the possibility of new 
lows in stock prices lower than those of last october cannot be 
dismissed 
it points out that shortterm interest rates are now more than 1 
percentage point higher than they were one year ago at the stock 
market peak while longterm treasury yields are around onehalf 
percentage point higher 
in fact highquality corporate bonds offer a return nearly 2 
percentage points higher than that available on stocks a situation 
that is out of whack with recent history 
over the past 20 years stock earnings yields have averaged the 
same as longterm bond yields prior to 1984 says wright bond 
yields as high as todays would have precluded a stock 
priceearnings ratio of more than 10 
thus says wright the current stock market priceearnings 
multiple of 12 while only average for the postwar period may yet 
prove to be excessive in todays environment 
is the obsession with interest rates overdone does it ignore 
positive factors perhaps 
investor confidence could be supported by other aspects of the 
economy that show it to be stronger than a year ago despite its 
advanced age corporate earnings are setting records 
priceearnings ratios have shrunk corporate takeover activities 
continue to remove stock from the market thus creating a relative 
shortage of equities and investor psychology is much healthier 
a year ago you may recall investors floated on a cloud of 
euphoria and cared little for such fundamental considerations as 
real value now they fear the market they study fundamentals and 
they dont take chances 
wright agrees that these are indeed encouraging signs 
nevertheless wright and a host of other analysts wonder if those 
interest rates still might not knock prices down as they did last 
year 
so long as the threat exists says wright the bull market will 
have to wait when will it come you can be confident it 
concludes that a new bull market will get under way next year 
which means in effect that those interestrate worries will 
have abated 
