<TEXT>
the stock and bond markets rallied powerfully today after the 
labor department said the us unemployment rate rose to 56 
percent in august a figure that eased concerns the economy was 
growing too briskly 
the news that more americans were out of work cheered up 
investors who were worried that the federal reserve would have to 
raise interest rates to stave off inflation 
bond prices staged their biggest rally of the year driving 
yields back down to the levels of early august the yield on the 
treasurys benchmark 30year bond plunged to 903 percent from 930 
percent late thursday 
on wall street the dow jones average of 30 industrials jumped 
5334 points to 205565 by 130 pm edt 
the dow jones averages rise triggered a new york stock exchange 
prohibition on member firms use of nyse automated systems to 
perform a form of program trading known as index arbitrage the 
prohibition kicks in when the index rises or falls more than 50 
points 
the dollar fell slightly against most major currencies as 
investors decided that us interest rates would drop and make 
dollardenominated securities less attractive to global investors 
the labor department said the number of jobless americans jumped 
by 226000 in august to 6851000 as four months of hiring booms 
in factories and retail stores screeched to a halt 
the august figure was 02 percentage point higher than julys 
civilian jobless rate of 54 percent which was up 01 percent from 
junes 14year low of 53 percent 
a separate survey of business payrolls which many economists 
consider a more reliable indicator of the economys health showed 
219000 new jobs in august well below the 400000 average monthly 
increase in june and july 
todays unemployment data followed another government report 
showing the first quarterly decline in us labor productivity 
since 1986 
analysts said the report indicated that hardpressed businesses 
were being forced to hire lessskilled workers to fill job openings 
the labor department said thursday that the labor productivity 
of nonfarm businesses fell 14 percent in the apriljune period 
less than the originally reported 17 percent decline 
the report was roughly in line with expectations and did not 
have a large effect on the financial markets 
stock prices fell thursday in sympathy with previous declines in 
tokyo and london the dow jones average of 30 industrials dropped 
2934 points to 200231 
other reports thursday took some of the edge off fears of 
inflation and rising interest rates 
august sales figures indicated the nations largest general 
retailers were unable to escape their 18monthold slump as weather 
and continuing problems in apparel lines kept customers away 
also the commerce department said construction spending rose 
12 percent in july after slumping in june 
on productivity the labor department released revised figures 
showing productivity fell at an annual rate of 14 percent in the 
apriljune period the statistic measures the output per hour of 
labor for nonfarm businesses 
labor costs shot up at a 57 percent annual rate the biggest 
increase since 1986 reflecting the productivity declines and wage 
and benefit increases averaging 42 percent annually 
charles renfro of alphametrics an economic forecasting firm in 
bala cynwyd pa said the figures indicate that an inflationary 
head of steam is building 
economic output in the second quarter rose 33 percent but to 
achieve the increased output businesses had to raise the number of 
hours worked by their employees by 66 percent 
analysts said the increase in hours and consequent decrease in 
productivity reflects a hiring boom in which employers at a time of 
decadelow unemployment are relying more on lessskilled workers 
