<TEXT>
the nations unemployment rate rose to 56 
percent in august as four months of hiring booms on factory 
assembly lines and in retail stores came to an abrupt halt the 
government said today 
the labor department said the number of jobless americans jumped 
by 226000 to 6851000 in august while the number of those with 
jobs rose by only 121000 to 115180000 
the 02 percentage point increase from julys civilian jobless 
rate of 54 percent followed a 01 percent rise from junes 14year 
low of 53 percent 
the report sparked a rally on wall street the dow jones average 
of 30 industrial stocks climbed sharply in early trading as 
investors apparently viewed the unemployment rise as reducing 
upward pressure on interest rates and inflation 
most of the increased joblessness was suffered by adult men 
with their unemployment rate rising 04 percentage points to 49 
percent the jobless rate among adult women meanwhile fell from 
51 percent to 48 percent the 
a separate survey of business payrolls which many economists 
consider a more reliable indicator of the economys health showed 
219000 new jobs in august well below the 400000 average monthly 
increase in june and july 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
labor department said 
white house spokesman b jay cooper in california with the 
vacationing president called the report good news 
the continued strong gains in august payroll employment 
confirm that the longest peacetime expansion in us history 
continued through its 69th month the spokesman said 
despite the increase in unemployment cooper said the 
administration was cheered by the good numbers underneath the 
overall numbers such as in the jobless rate for women 
the last time the civilian unemployment rate was at 56 percent 
was in may 
the goodsproducing side of the economy lost jobs for the first 
time since last january with employment in manufacturing dropping 
by 5000 after a 70000 jump in july 
the labor department said small employment gains in printing and 
publishing and exportrelated industries such as machinery and 
electrical equipment were more than offset by 9000 job losses in 
textile and apparel plants and smaller declines in several other 
manufacturing industries 
employment in oil and gas drilling also declined slightly but 
it rose a minuscule 3000 jobs in construction 
on the services side of the economy large monthly increases in 
retail trade hiring 80000 in july alone slowed to just 23000 
new jobs last month virtually all in grocery stores 
other recent highgrowth job areas also slowed business 
services such as temporary help firms added just 16000 new 
workers compared with average monthly increases of 60000 through 
the spring and early summer 
new employment in health services which the government predicts 
will be the largest area of job growth in the 1990s as the baby 
boom population ages slowed to 22000 in august it also had been 
rising an average 30000 a month in the past year 
the labor market showed less strength in august than earlier 
in the year said labor statistics commissioner janet l norwood 
looked at over a somewhat longer period however the rate has 
hovered in the 53 percent to 56 percent range since last march 
and is 04 percentage point below the leval a year ago 
ms norwood said one encouraging sign was that the number of 
people working parttime involuntarily because they could not find 
fulltime jobs returned to the bottom of the 52 million to 56 
million range within which it has been fluctuating for more than a 
year 
the proportion of workingage persons holding jobs remained at 
its record level of 623 percent ms norwood told the joint 
economic committee of congress 
other data in the report however suggested that the economy 
might be slowing the average workweek declined by 20 minutes to 
346 hours and manufacturing overtime fell by 01 hours to 38 
hours a week on average 
that sent weekly earnings down nearly a full percentage point as 
average hourly wages for nonsupervisory workers held steady at 
924 
in the past 12 months the labor department said wages have 
risen an average of only 31 percent decreasing the buying power 
of workers after taking inflation into account by half a percent 
a separate calculation that includes the 17 million uniformed 
armed forces in the job market showed a jobless rate of 55 percent 
last month up from 54 percent in july 
the government offered this other figures on unemployment in 
august 
whites 49 percent up from 47 percent in july 
blacks 113 percent down from 114 percent 
hispanics 84 percent up from 8 percent 
teenagers 158 percent up from 152 percent 
black teengers 158 percent up from 152 percent 
private analysts had anticipated the overall jobless rate might 
rise prior to todays report 
i think were going to be stuck near 55 percent for the rest 
of the year said roger brinner of data resources inc a 
lexington mass economic consulting firm employment is not 
going to fall its just not going to rise as fast as it has been 
brinner like other economists believes too many people many 
of them with only marginal skills have been hired in recent months 
in relation to the rate of economic growth 
we may be at the point where we have absorbed most of labors 
skilled capacity said charles renfro chief economist for the 
forecasting firm of alphametrics also of bala cynwyd anything 
less than an uptick in the jobless rate will be a real danger sign 
that the economy is overheating 
bruce steinberg an economist for merrill lynch noted that new 
claims for unemployment compensation rose slightly last month an 
indication of increased layoffs in some areas 
steinberg believes there is still room for the jobless rate to 
fall over the next several months but not in august 
