<TEXT>
washington public power supply systems 
executive board on friday approved a settlement removing wppss from 
a securities fraud case that goes to trial next week in tucson 
ariz 
the board met in private for an hour and then approved the 
settlement in a brief public meeting 
the fraud lawsuit is the result of the 1983 default by wppss on 
225 billion worth of bonds sold to begin construction on two 
nuclear power plants in washington state the plants were 
abandoned only partially complete in 1982 
removal of wppss from the case leaves 21 washington and oregon 
utilities three engineering firms and a financial advisory firm as 
defendants trial is scheduled to begin wednesday in federal court 
ray foleen a member of the executive board said wppss 
settlement could be the first step in settling all remaining 
bondholder claims 
its my belief it is in the best interest of the ratepayers of 
the region that we get this matter settled he said i hope the 
supply systems action will be a positive element in the region and 
become a catalyst for further reasonable settlement 
by leaving the case the supply system will save millions of 
dollars in legal costs it already has spent more than 23 million 
over five years to get to trial and had budgeted 7 million more 
for a year of trial 
much of wppss trialcost savings however are expected to be 
picked up by remaining defendants 
</TEXT>
